<subSubSection id="FDEF094AA9440FEE8CAD239E40F67AD2" pageId="3" pageNumber="456" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="BE5D093119AD47175B7C53CEBE1A202C" pageId="3" pageNumber="456">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9BEAA2F89E4E5424B9E4283066FB1962" pageId="3" pageNumber="456">
Other than showing a reasonable variation in shell size, the species displays little conchological variation (
<figureCitation id="F9CB15A2A73F447F5EF8479A51F99828" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Hyperaulax ridleyi. A-E. Lectotype, NHMUK 1888.6.27.106. F-I. Paralectotypes  1 to  4 (in order), NHMUK 1888.6.27.107 - 110. J. Extreme form, large and with thick callus, NHMUK 1888.6.27.88 - 94. K. Weathered specimen, ZMS unnumbered (ex Heimburg colln.). L. Protoconch detail (same specimen from K)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.95.38259.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/339175" pageId="3" pageNumber="456" tableDoi="10.3897/zse.95.38259.figure2">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). Rare specimens, however, do deviate from the typical form, for instance by having broader shells with shorter spires (
<figureCitation id="3C855FA4DAE7803B93E55EECD4F4DF0D" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Hyperaulax ridleyi. A-E. Lectotype, NHMUK 1888.6.27.106. F-I. Paralectotypes  1 to  4 (in order), NHMUK 1888.6.27.107 - 110. J. Extreme form, large and with thick callus, NHMUK 1888.6.27.88 - 94. K. Weathered specimen, ZMS unnumbered (ex Heimburg colln.). L. Protoconch detail (same specimen from K)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.95.38259.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/339175" pageId="3" pageNumber="456" tableDoi="10.3897/zse.95.38259.figure2">
Fig. 2
<normalizedToken id="758D665E037C205C80FAB5A2D5DD1912" originalValue="F–I">F-I</normalizedToken>
</figureCitation>
) or by having a palatal tooth (
<figureCitation id="EF9DF8A79B7EB715148560FE8406605A" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Hyperaulax ridleyi. A-E. Lectotype, NHMUK 1888.6.27.106. F-I. Paralectotypes  1 to  4 (in order), NHMUK 1888.6.27.107 - 110. J. Extreme form, large and with thick callus, NHMUK 1888.6.27.88 - 94. K. Weathered specimen, ZMS unnumbered (ex Heimburg colln.). L. Protoconch detail (same specimen from K)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.95.38259.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/339175" pageId="3" pageNumber="456" tableDoi="10.3897/zse.95.38259.figure2">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
, lectotype). The color might vary from more ochre tones to more reddish-brown ones, but the single white spiral band on the mid-section of the whorl is always present. 
<taxonomicName id="37FD4F60C17335BF449481539F399981" class="Gastropoda" family="Odontostomidae" genus="Hyperaulax" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hyperaulax ridelyi" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="3" pageNumber="456" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="ridelyi">
<emphasis id="35F2C8131F5FA41EEC56B438EBDECB41" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="456">Hyperaulax ridelyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be easily distinguished from its only congener, 
<taxonomicName id="5C5A47F77BE4E6698A7A1420AE0AF8C6" genus="H." lsidName="H. ramagei" pageId="3" pageNumber="456" rank="species" species="ramagei">
<emphasis id="88477A62C6B320275A9A7D35F686E3CC" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="456">H. ramagei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, by its smaller shell (with a single spiral white band) and more elongated and slender shell profile. Moreover, its protoconch has a more raised ridge and the riblets of its sculpture are much more anastomosed. Finally, 
<taxonomicName id="39A42A3FF6E97B2DE68CB17D5E2D8525" genus="H." lsidName="H. ridleyi" pageId="3" pageNumber="456" rank="species" species="ridleyi">
<emphasis id="39D97213B5B9ED41D6B853373C7A6224" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="456">H. ridleyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
typically bears no apertural dentition (although a weak palatal tooth might be present; 
<figureCitation id="DBD8B59EFAB684690205304218212A0D" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Hyperaulax ridleyi. A-E. Lectotype, NHMUK 1888.6.27.106. F-I. Paralectotypes  1 to  4 (in order), NHMUK 1888.6.27.107 - 110. J. Extreme form, large and with thick callus, NHMUK 1888.6.27.88 - 94. K. Weathered specimen, ZMS unnumbered (ex Heimburg colln.). L. Protoconch detail (same specimen from K)." figureDoi="10.3897/zse.95.38259.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/339175" pageId="3" pageNumber="456" tableDoi="10.3897/zse.95.38259.figure2">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AE03E15B8F2570C4F9732BB1C0442994" pageId="3" pageNumber="456">
Unfortunately, not much can be found in the literature about this 
<normalizedToken id="1EB30EE98E6B69232807AC684613424D" originalValue="species’">species'</normalizedToken>
habitat or habits, but the museum labels point to a variety of collection locales, albeit more usually referring to dead shells only. In any event, this species has been reported alive from forested areas, mangrove, beaches, dunes, and gardens.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
